Notebook[{
Cell["Problem Set 14 \[LongDash] Goes with Chapter 11", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.980612196187374*^9, 3.980612211422606*^9}, {
  3.983968223819804*^9, 3.9839682248940153`*^9}, {3.9839695309872723`*^9, 
  3.983969535158185*^9}, {3.983980503040326*^9, 
  3.983980505030868*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"821ff873-b417-423b-a8a4-\
5a0d4019d7d8"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["For Quantum Mechanics, Thursday, Apr. 2, 2026", "Subtitle",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.980620822912372*^9, 3.980620841363928*^9}, {
  3.9839682338068867`*^9, 
  3.9839682414390907`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"cfc20ab9-f802-4f42-a532-\
dae68ab4fb47"],

Cell["\<\
The reading that goes with the problem set is Sections III-11-1, III-11-2, \
III-11-3. Please also take a look at III-11-4, because it might be nice to \
discuss that in class. We are putting off III-11-6.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.983968514603891*^9, 3.983968519566084*^9}, {
  3.983969208149592*^9, 3.983969221078026*^9}, {3.983978646917409*^9, 
  3.983978661829021*^9}, {3.98397871329557*^9, 3.983978749488029*^9}, {
  3.983980111776696*^9, 
  3.983980120896441*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"78dd3dcc-f0bf-4b02-97f8-\
7d7ae53d90e0"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["1. How do the Pauli Matrices \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Transform\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9806122473340683`*^9, 3.980612272489726*^9}, {
  3.980621891551169*^9, 3.980621896529681*^9}, {3.9839682628456497`*^9, 
  3.9839682667006483`*^9}, {3.9839683063812027`*^9, 3.983968307248416*^9}, {
  3.983968355074514*^9, 
  3.983968364718157*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e415f264-7369-4b76-b8c7-\
29a8008f0537"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This problem is based on a statement at the middle of p. 11-4. For at least \
one Pauli matrix and one transformation, we want to see that the Pauli matrix \
transforms like a vector. We should do ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "x"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "2c9fe1bb-b329-43f7-a0e7-518748021fc9"],
 ", and the transformation could be a rotation around the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"y", "-", "axis"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "79c7a2e7-3081-40c9-896f-a7040dd0d101"],
 ". We expect ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "x"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b873d5f6-854e-4ad1-9418-d11c352a52f4"],
 " to \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]transform\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] into some \
combination of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "x"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "375fbedf-cbf0-4c68-967b-4f6fd1589b6b"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "z"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "dba26b59-08b1-4ad1-a98f-a76012ba94a6"],
 ". Now I will try to explain what that might mean. Also, Feynman warned us \
that this is going to be a lot of algebra. That is why we are only doing one \
Pauli matrix and just a simple rotation by \[Phi] about the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"y", "-", "axis"}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "3129ced6-38cd-4ae3-87f5-a442e0dd29d0"],
 ". Let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s get more precise....\n\nLet ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"|", "\[VeryThinSpace]", 
    RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ">"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "f66b4114-c3a3-43e0-a482-e72e0dd78d95"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"|", "\[VeryThinSpace]", 
    RowBox[{"\[Chi]", ">"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "8a0993bc-9cc4-4a10-bba1-32d083a3fd72"],
 " be two states. Let ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["R", "y"], "(", "\[Phi]", ")"}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "2e316a47-c6a2-4d4e-9cca-e11195553175"],
 " be a rotation about the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"y", "-", "axis"}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "6e0ef362-553c-4f46-9df9-4869bc13a5a3"],
 ". I am deliberately being a little vague about whether we are rotating the \
apparatus that measures the states defined in basis ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["S", TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "886a9c1f-2fec-4a56-b09d-4e6815b7d9fd"],
 " to a new basis ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["T", TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "52f904a4-04a9-49e1-a85c-f1cefdaff563"],
 ", or whether we are rotating the states themselves, because I am frankly \
not sure which we mean. Whichever the interpretation is, you can find the \
effect of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["R", "y"], "(", "\[Phi]", ")"}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "a963dd00-306c-4f62-b99b-6b034715dba4"],
 " back in the tables on p. III-6-14.\n\nNow consider ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["R", "y"], "(", "\[Phi]", ")"}], "|", 
    RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ">"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "ae7d2bd0-fc76-4df4-9dd1-bbef492777cb"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["R", "y"], "(", "\[Phi]", ")"}], "|", 
    RowBox[{"\[Chi]", ">"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "c0e838d8-72ae-461a-8f7e-0e318fcc42c8"],
 ". Give them names ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"|", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Phi]"], ">", "\[Congruent]", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["R", "y"], "(", "\[Phi]", ")"}]}], "|", 
    RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ">"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "4aecb096-4c4c-4fe4-ad3c-c9878538f0fc"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"|", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Chi]", "\[Phi]"], ">", "\[Congruent]", " ", 
     RowBox[{
      SubscriptBox["R", "y"], "(", "\[Phi]", ")"}]}], "|", 
    RowBox[{"\[Chi]", ">"}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "111ae2e1-c58e-4103-aef5-acae9b9a67db"],
 ".\n\nWhat this problem boils down to is calculating ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"<", 
     SubscriptBox["\[Chi]", "\[Phi]"]}], "|", 
    SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "x"], "|", 
    RowBox[{
     SubscriptBox["\[Psi]", "\[Phi]"], ">"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "b488a5e0-f3df-4e9c-9270-0d936113514b"],
 " and hopefully discovering that it is some combination of",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"<", "\[Chi]"}], "|", 
    SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "x"], "|", 
    RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ">"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "e0a76ac5-6bf9-4873-a103-b249e68aff9f"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"<", "\[Chi]"}], "|", 
    SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "z"], "|", 
    RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ">"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "fa2ab1da-be77-416a-9948-d8977e045148"],
 ". The combination has to be independent of what ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"|", "\[VeryThinSpace]", 
    RowBox[{"\[Psi]", ">"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "2363d80b-6533-4de2-89a9-c10532c8bc43"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"|", "\[VeryThinSpace]", 
    RowBox[{"\[Chi]", ">"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "7ea1641b-6349-424a-acb0-867fc75671f4"],
 " are chosen. They could be any states whatsoever!\n\nIt might help to use \
this: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "x"], "=", 
    RowBox[{"|", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"S", "+"}], ">", "<", 
      RowBox[{"S", "-"}]}], "|", "    ", 
     RowBox[{"+", "    ", 
      RowBox[{"|", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"S", "-"}], " ", ">", "<", 
        RowBox[{"S", "+"}]}], "|", " "}]}]}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"d3b73b18-8c64-45ab-82eb-194c7f30d040"],
 ".\n\nHopefully we\[CloseCurlyQuote]ll find a combination of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "x"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "d415e4ce-5625-4a7e-9d6f-a376e526adf5"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "y"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "5994ce84-8d6d-447a-a7b1-85354909fcc6"],
 " that makes perfect sense as if the \[Sigma]\[CloseCurlyQuote]s were \
undergoing a vector transformation by \[Phi] around the ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"y", "-", "axis"}], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "fad1edc3-529f-4863-9879-3edcb115d14c"],
 ". Apply the right-hand rule carefully if you want to get precise about the \
difference between \[Phi] and -\[Phi] or between transforming the states and \
transforming the apparatus."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.98396923381458*^9, 3.983969236753495*^9}, {
  3.983969276745022*^9, 3.983969359949225*^9}, {3.983977511570601*^9, 
  3.983977714167883*^9}, {3.983977757358551*^9, 3.983977765442893*^9}, {
  3.98397781623603*^9, 3.9839783337875223`*^9}, {3.983978384006692*^9, 
  3.983978395168198*^9}, {3.983978459381966*^9, 3.983978562089431*^9}, {
  3.98397878774242*^9, 3.983978871581029*^9}, {3.983979650250177*^9, 
  3.983980087147643*^9}, {3.983980138034999*^9, 3.9839802111384974`*^9}, {
  3.98398079340959*^9, 
  3.983980793736505*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1b5dabef-4955-4afd-b6aa-\
d35ec6643306"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["2. Feynman Problem 78.1(a)", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9806122473340683`*^9, 3.980612272489726*^9}, {
  3.980621891551169*^9, 3.980621896529681*^9}, {3.9839682628456497`*^9, 
  3.9839682667006483`*^9}, {3.9839683063812027`*^9, 3.983968307248416*^9}, {
  3.983968371163476*^9, 3.983968371285726*^9}, {3.983968411563058*^9, 
  3.983968411680181*^9}, {3.983978620892232*^9, 3.983978631838666*^9}, {
  3.983978783603118*^9, 3.983978784037109*^9}, {3.983978869597402*^9, 
  3.983978870287882*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"eb6fbccf-5c00-47b8-bc54-\
55886a79d0a9"],

Cell["\<\
Just do this problem mechanically. This time we aren\[CloseCurlyQuote]t \
trying to prove they are vectors. We are just discovering some vector-like \
identities. Only do Part (a). I have no idea what Feynman wants in (b).\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.983968445288169*^9, 3.983968483909388*^9}, {
  3.983978571150169*^9, 3.983978590753533*^9}, {3.983980098336513*^9, 
  3.983980099340966*^9}, {3.983980811977839*^9, 
  3.983980815977108*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a8892d36-a9c5-4d5e-9678-\
24eb0fcc34e6"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]]
},
